title: Examples
text: Let’s suppose interested evolution unemployment rate sex last quarters. case, can use get_many_data() function, shown following example: Next, can calculate unemployment rate men, women nationwide. Finally, can graph results.
code: ene_serie <-  get_many_data(dataset = "ene", from = "2022-09-aso", to = "2023-07-jja", col_list = c("ano_trimestre", "mes_central", "cae_especifico", "fact_cal", "sexo"), memory_warning_limit = 10000) unemployment_serie <- ene_serie %>%    map_df(., . %>% mutate(fact_cal = as.numeric(gsub(",", ".", fact_cal)),                          work_force = if_else(cae_especifico %in% 1:9, 1, 0),                          unemployed = if_else(cae_especifico %in% 8:9, 1, 0)) %>%            filter(work_force == 1) %>%             group_by(ano_trimestre, mes_central) %>%             summarise(work_force = round(sum(work_force*fact_cal), 0),                      unemployed = round(sum(unemployed*fact_cal), 0)) %>%             mutate(unemployment_rate = round((unemployed/work_force)*100, 1))    ) %>%    bind_rows(., map_df(ene_serie, . %>% mutate(fact_cal = as.numeric(gsub(",", ".", fact_cal)),                                       work_force = if_else(cae_especifico %in% 1:9, 1, 0),                                       unemployed = if_else(cae_especifico %in% 8:9, 1, 0)) %>%                         filter(work_force == 1) %>%                          group_by(ano_trimestre, mes_central, sexo) %>%                          summarise(work_force = round(sum(work_force*fact_cal), 0),                                   unemployed = round(sum(unemployed*fact_cal), 0)) %>%                          mutate(unemployment_rate = round((unemployed/work_force)*100, 1)))) %>%    mutate(sexo = if_else(is.na(sexo), "Nationwide total",                         if_else(sexo==1, "Men", "Women")),          ano_trimestre=as.factor(ano_trimestre),          periodo = case_when(mes_central==1 ~ "dic-feb",                              mes_central==2 ~ "ene-mar",                              mes_central==3 ~ "feb-abr",                              mes_central==4 ~ "mar-may",                              mes_central==5 ~ "abr-jun",                              mes_central==6 ~ "may-jul",                              mes_central==7 ~ "jun-ago",                              mes_central==8 ~ "jul-sep",                              mes_central==9 ~ "ago-oct",                              mes_central==10 ~ "sep-nov",                              mes_central==11 ~ "oct-dic",                              mes_central==12 ~ "nov-ene"),          periodo = factor(periodo,  levels=c("dic-feb","ene-mar","feb-abr","mar-may","abr-jun","may-jul",                                              "jun-ago","jul-sep","ago-oct",                                              "sep-nov","oct-dic","nov-ene")))  unemployment_serie #> # A tibble: 33 × 7 #> # Groups:   ano_trimestre [2] #>    ano_trimestre mes_central work_force unemployed unemployment_rate sexo        #>    <fct>               <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl>             <dbl> <chr>       #>  1 2023                    7    9895618     890175               9   Nationwide… #>  2 2023                    6    9896817     868170               8.8 Nationwide… #>  3 2023                    5    9877419     842305               8.5 Nationwide… #>  4 2023                    4    9876146     841916               8.5 Nationwide… #>  5 2023                    3    9860631     853902               8.7 Nationwide… #>  6 2023                    2    9876077     869932               8.8 Nationwide… #>  7 2023                    1    9854774     824612               8.4 Nationwide… #>  8 2022                   12    9795863     787317               8   Nationwide… #>  9 2022                   11    9730299     765069               7.9 Nationwide… #> 10 2022                   10    9650165     767075               7.9 Nationwide… #> # ℹ 23 more rows #> # ℹ 1 more variable: periodo <fct> graph <- unemployment_serie %>%   group_by(sexo) %>%   plot_ly(x=~interaction(periodo, ano_trimestre), y=~unemployment_rate, group=~sexo,           type="scatter", color=~sexo, mode="lines+markers") %>%    layout(xaxis = list(title = 'Quarter'),           yaxis = list(title = 'Unemployment rate (%)'),          legend = list(orientation = 'h', xanchor = "center", x = 0.5, y = 1.1))  graph

title: Examples
text: Continuing National Employment Survey (ENE), example use occupational category variable estimate number employed people quarter occupational category.
code: ene_serie <-  get_many_data(dataset = "ene", from = "2022-09-aso", to = "2023-07-jja", col_list = c("ano_trimestre", "mes_central", "cae_especifico", "fact_cal", "categoria_ocupacion"), memory_warning_limit = 10000) category_serie <- ene_serie %>%    map_df(., . %>%             mutate(fact_cal = as.numeric(gsub(",", ".", fact_cal)),                   employed = if_else(cae_especifico %in% 1:7, 1, 0),                   ocupational_category = ifelse(categoria_ocupacion==1, "Employers",                                                 ifelse(categoria_ocupacion==2, "Own-account workers",                                                        ifelse(categoria_ocupacion==3, "Private wage earners",                                                               ifelse(categoria_ocupacion==4, "Public wage earners",                                                                      ifelse(categoria_ocupacion %in% 5:6, "Domestic workers", "Unpaid family workers")))))) %>%               filter(employed == 1) %>%             group_by(ano_trimestre, mes_central, ocupational_category) %>%             summarise(employed = round(sum(employed*fact_cal), 0))) %>%    pivot_wider(names_from = ocupational_category, values_from = employed)   tbl <- category_serie %>%   kbl() %>%   kable_paper("hover", full_width = F)  tbl

text: inedata package allows download datasets produced INE Chile. package communicates API REST, makes possible retrieve many household survey datasets using R code. available data provided API corresponds files published INE’s web site. moment API restricted institutional network. package works environment. hope make API available general public soon possible.

text: get_catalog() returns dataframe containing datasets available repository versions dataset parameter specified. following datasets currently available: EPF ENUSC ESI ENE also adds summary data form number columns rows per dataset (n_col n_row columns, respectively). survey column contains survey dataset comes . version column indicates year quarter dataset collected. dataset parameter retrieves information specific survey. example using ene, returns available versions survey. store file version june-august-september quarter 2011 (2011-08-jas) variable called file.

title: Testing
text: get_columns() function returns columns specific file. requires two mandatory parameters, namely dataset version fetch specific column names. already name one available versions ene survey.

title: Testing
text: get_data() function allows us bring dataset specific survey. function four parameters: dataset, version, col_list save_where. instance, can get ene data specific quarter. version parameter specified return newest version survey. col_list can select variables dataset, specified select columns. Meanwhile, save_where allows us define dataset stored. four options: renviron: store memory R enviroment. size overloads ram memory show warning prompt recommending save data working directory asking user wants proceed. disk: store directory called data/ working directory, R enviroment. : store parts. no_message: users responsibility, show warning datasets stored R enviroment. Important note: highly recommend downloading entire dataset. Instead, consider selecting specific columns, full download consume substantial amount time storage space. get_many_data() function allows download one dataset time. example getting versions december-january-february (2022-01-def) february-march-april (2022-03-fma) 2022 quarters ene survey. function six parameters: dataset, , , col_list, save_where, memory_warning_limit. fromand arguments mandatory used filter selected periods versions particular survey. memory_warning_limit argument allows set memory limit triggers warning downloading R memory. output list dataframes. case can see df_list contains 3 elements. can convert three dataframes one table Important note: different versions dataset always compatible, , bind_rows() method won’t always work. always careful joining multiple versions check structure proceeding.
